## My Habits (auto-distilled · last updated 2026-02-14)

- Reply in English; be concise and lead with the conclusion.
- Before changing code, propose the plan and scope first; wait for approval to proceed.
- Keep changes minimal and focused; don't refactor unrelated code opportunistically.
- Verify claims against the real code before concluding; cite `file:line`, and say so when unsure.
- Default to Python for one-off scripts and CLIs.
- Prefer plugin/injectable designs: decouple strategy from core, sensible defaults, config over code changes.
- When fixing bugs, narrow the blast radius — avoid touching shared helpers used by every caller.
- For large changes, favor phased delivery: ship a minimal/shadow version first, then scale up.
- Reuse existing patterns in the repo (naming, layering, style) instead of inventing a new one.
- Surface any newly added functions that end up uncalled; flag real dead code for removal.
<!-- END habit-distiller -->
